@node Registration "MyLang · Registration"

To register, simply e-mail your name to @{"herrmic@poczta.onet.pl" system "OpenURL mailto:herrmic@poczta.onet.pl"}. You'll receive your personal keyfile in few days.

The whole easy registration idea is taken from OnyxSoft.

@endnode

@node Introduction "MyLang · Introduction"

@{b}MyLang@{ub} is useful vocabulary trainer. It has all functions you need (I hope so). For full list see @{"features" link Features}. I made this program because I need one and couldn't find anything similar on aminet (all programs that I've seen either lacks some important features or are too expensive for me). After few hours I realized that it is quite good, so why don't let other people use it?
I made @{b}MyLang@{ub} free because I think that programs like this (intended for use by students) should be free (the most students I know don't have lots of money, but if they had, they prefer to buy a beer rather than educational software).

@endnode

@node Features "MyLang · Features"

Features list:

· teach, test and translator modes,

· can work in both directions (f.ex. "English -> Polish" and "Polish -> English")

· after each session displays stats window

· after each session you can automaticly create new dictionaries containing words you typed wrong

· possiblity to load selected dictionaries only

· each word can have unlimited number of translations (works in both directions)

· internal vocabulary editor

· any samples can be played after every answer (via datatypes)

· comfortable and easy-to-use interface

· uses MUI by Stefan Stuntz

· 100% localized

@endnode

@node Requirements "MyLang · Requirements"

@{b}MyLang@{ub} requires:

· AmigaOS 3.0

· MUI 3.8

· BetterString.mcc

Memory requirements are really minimal, so don't worry about.

Also recommended:

· TextEditor.mcc (for vocabulary editor)

· some sound datatypes (for ability to play samples)

@endnode

@node Installation "MyLang · Installation"

Simply copy program's drawer wherever you want. I don't think that there is need for Installer-script.
If you have OS 3.5 or higher installed you may want to use other icon (see "Icons" directory).



NOTE: If you used previous version, please delete "Prefs.default" file - it is obsolete due to new preferences handling system.

@endnode

@node Usage "MyLang · Usage"

For now, there are no shell nor workbench options. Everything should be set within program itself.

@endnode

@node Dictionaries "MyLang · Dictionaries"

Dictionaries are simple ascii files. Each line contains definition of one word. Comments are allowed (just type # as the first character) - such lines are ignored.
Each dictionary line should consists of

          @{b}word1@{ub} = @{b}word2@{ub}

pair, where word1 is a word in first language with word2 as transtation to second one (and vice-versa: word1 can be treated as translation of word2).
Exception is first line which describes the languages:

          @{b}language1@{ub} = @{b}language2@{ub}

Here you should type what languages the file contain.


@{b}NOTE:@{ub} It is good custom to type each language name as "english", "deutsch", "svenska" etc. (NOT "english", "german", "swedish"). It greatly simplifies exchange of vocabularies.


There is also possiblity to specify several traslations of one word. It's very simple, just type:

          someword = translation1
          someword = translation2
or
          someword1 = translation
          someword2 = translation

This works between different dictionaries as well (in fact, after loading, all dictionaries are joined in memory).

Since version 1.5 there is a second way of entering multiple translations: with use of semicolon. Such entry should look like:

          someword1 = translation1;translation2;translation3
or
          someword1;someword2 = translation
or
          someword1;someword2 = translation1;translation2

The way how such words behave is controlled via "Severe semicolon" setting. See an example:

          a;b;c = 1;2;3;4;5

Say, you are asked for translation of "a;b;c". With the setting off, any answer containing some of the digits is correct ("1", "2", "3", "1;4", "2;3;5", etc...). But with "Severe semicolon" on, you should supply all of the digits (in any order), so the only correct answers are "3;4;2;1;5", "1;5;2;4;3" etc...


@{b}NOTE@{ub}: Do not mix these two methods within one dictionary.


Number of words per file is unlimited (as long as you have enough free memory to load them all).

@endnode

@node Samples "MyLang · Samples"

Since version 1.4 @{b}MyLang@{ub} is able to play samples to additionally indicate if your answer was correct or wrong. It uses datatypes for this purpose so usually you don't need to bother about various file formats.

@{b}MyLang@{ub} uses simple directory structure to allow easy management of your samples. All samples are divided on sets. Each set consists of two directories:

· @{b}Correct/@{ub}

  Here you store samples for all your correct answers.

· @{b}Wrong/@{ub}

  Samples from this drawer are played if your answer is wrong.

All samples are played in random order. Their number is unlimited, @{b}MyLang@{ub} keeps only one sample in memory at once. You can select which set to use via @{"Preferences window" link Preferences}.

@endnode

@node MainWindow "MyLang · Main window"

Main window consists of several buttons and string gadgets. There is also pulldown menu, described at the bottom of this page.

The string gadgets have no labels, but are appropriately:

· user input

  Here you enter your answers while in teach or test mode. When in translator, here you type the word you want translation(s) of.

· teacher/examiner output

  The word you should translate when in teach or test mode.

· translator output

  Beside it's obvious function, here is also displayed correct answer (if yours was wrong).



@{b}Gadgets@{ub}
_______

· @{b}Teach@{ub}

  Allows you to enter teach mode. You will be asked for translation of all words. If you give wrong answer, the word will be repeated soon. So "teacher" won't end until you answer everything right, what means (at teast in theory) that you know all the words.

· @{b}Test@{ub}

  Enters test mode. You will be asked for translations of all words. "Examiner" ends when you answer to all questions (no matter if answers were wrong or right). This mode is intended to check your abilities achieved by hours (?) of learning.

· @{b}Translator@{ub}

  Program will try to translate words you enter.

· @{b}Direction@{ub}

  Cycle gadget to choose direction of translation. It can behave strangely, but this is intended by me (if somebody wants, I can explain this).

· @{b}Summary@{ub}

  Ends current mode instantly (imagine that program clicks "summary" by itself when mode ends normally)

· @{b}Load dictionaries...@{ub}

  Allows you to load new dictionary files (displays file requester with multiselection available)



@{b}Menus@{ub}
_____

· Project

      · About ................ some informations about the program

      · About MUI ............ MUI informations

      · Quit ................. quits the program

· Vocabularies

      · Open new editor ...... spreads new vocabulary editor

· Preferences

      · Program .............. pops up Preferences window

      · MUI .................. pops up MUI Preferences

      · Load ................. loads prefs from file

      · Save as .............. saves prefs to file

      · Save as default ...... saves prefs as defaults

@endnode

@node Editor "MyLang · Editor"

Starting from version 1.2, you can use internal vocabulary editor. There is possiblity to open several editor windows at once. Each window can have it's position and size saved exclusively.

The editor is highly customizable - just look at MUI prefs - TextEditor page.

Number of simultaneously opened windows is limited. Currently the maximum is 20. I can increase this easily if somebody needs it.

@endnode

@node Preferences "MyLang · Preferences"

Since version 1.2, preferences format have changed. It is no longer possible to edit options within text-editor. Use Preferences window of @{b}MyLang@{ub} instead.
Available options are:

· @{b}Fixed font@{ub}

  Set if the internal vocabulary editor should use fixed width font. It is recommended to turn on since display gets cleaner with it. Font name can be set with MUI prefs - TextEditor page.

· @{b}Vocabulary files path@{ub}

  Enter drawer which contains your dictionary files.

· @{b}Case sensitive@{ub}

  Set if word comparision should distinguish between upper- and lowercase. Useful to learn e.g. german nouns.

· @{b}Severe semicolon@{ub}

  If set, and word have multiple translations defined using semicolon, you'll need to enter all of them.

· @{b}Focus attention@{ub}

  If set, extra requester will be popped everytime you give wrong answer. This should improve learning process since the requester emphasizes the correct translation of the word.

· @{b}Protect session@{ub}

  Set if you want the program to confirm your every attempt to end unfinished session.

· @{b}Sound / Play sounds@{ub}

  Turn it on if you want samples to be played.

· @{b}Sound / Path@{ub}

  Drawer containing set of samples (see @{"Samples" link Samples} for more details).



NOTE: The old 'dictionary' option has been removed. If you really need it, just tell me.

@endnode

@node Dictionary "MyLang · Dictionary"

This window allows easy maintaining of dictionaries. It's main part is a list containing all loaded words. The list has five columns where first three are:

· @{b}State@{ub} - indicates if word is enabled

· @{b}Wrong@{ub} - after test/teach session: how many times you translated the word incorrectly

· @{b}Time@{ub}  - total number of seconds elapsed over the word

Below the list there are few buttons:

· @{b}All@{ub}, @{b}Toggle@{ub}, @{b}None@{ub} - to easily (un)select all of the words

The buttons @{b}Enable@{ub} and @{b}Disable@{ub} allow you to change the state of the selected words. The progam ignores disabled words completely, e.g.: you won't be asked for their translations during test/teach sessions. It is easy way to prevent being asked for translations of words you already know.
With the @{b}Save as@{ub} button you can save all enabled words into a new dictionary file.

NOTE: @{b}MyLang@{ub} internally uses 1/10 of second for greater precision and rounds down the result before it is displayed (to make display clearier). This is why often total number of seconds does not match sum of all individual times - this is not a bug.

@endnode

